  "prompt": "How can you know you are what you see in a mirror?",
  "response": "This is a philosophical question that touches on perception, identity, and self-awareness. Here are some perspectives:\n\n1. Physical evidence\n- The reflection moves when you move\n- Key physical features match your body\n- Detailed characteristics like facial features are consistent\n\n2. Philosophical perspectives\n- Ren\u00e9 Descartes' \"I think, therefore I am\" suggests self-awareness proves existence\n- The reflection is an image, not the actual self\n- Your consciousness confirms your identity beyond visual representation\n\n3. Psychological approaches\n- Mirror recognition develops around 18 months in humans\n- Self-recognition involves understanding your own image\n- Some animals like great apes can also recognize themselves\n\n4. Scientific considerations\n- Mirrors show a reversed image\n- Perceptual confirmation through multiple sensory inputs\n- Understanding of spatial relationships and body movement\n\n5. Metaphysical questions\n- Is the reflection truly \"you\"?\n- Identity is more than physical appearance\n- Consciousness transcends visual representation\n\nDifferent philosophical and scientific traditions offer various interpretations, but generally, multiple sensory and cognitive confirmations help verify mirror identity.",
